# IC-Ticker-LED

A scrolling LED message ticker built at the **Interface Cultures** department of the **Kunstuniversität Linz**. It receives messages via MQTT and displays them on a MAX7219 LED matrix, running on a TinyPICO (ESP32).

---

## Hardware

| Component | Details |
|---|---|
| Microcontroller | [TinyPICO](https://www.tinypico.com/) (ESP32) |
| Display | MAX7219 LED matrix — 12 modules daisy-chained (`FC16_HW` type) |
| Status LEDs | 8× NeoPixel (WS2812) on GPIO 27 |
| Buttons | Red (GPIO 14), Blue (GPIO 4) |
| Power | 5V via USB or external supply |

### Wiring (TinyPICO → MAX7219)

| MAX7219 Pin | TinyPICO Pin |
|---|---|
| VCC | 5V |
| GND | GND |
| DIN | GPIO 23 (MOSI) |
| CS / LOAD | GPIO 5 |
| CLK | GPIO 18 (SCK) |

> Pin definitions are set in `src/main.cpp` via `CLK_PIN`, `DATA_PIN`, `CS_PIN`.

---

## Software Setup

### Requirements

- [Visual Studio Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/)
- [PlatformIO IDE extension](https://platformio.org/install/ide?install=vscode)

### Install & Build

1. Clone the repository:
   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/artdanion/IC-Ticker-LED.git
   cd IC-Ticker-LED
   ```
2. Open the folder in VS Code — PlatformIO detects `platformio.ini` automatically.
3. PlatformIO installs all libraries on first build (see dependencies below).
4. Click **Build** (✓ in the bottom toolbar) to compile.

### First Flash (USB)

For the very first upload, connect the TinyPICO via USB and temporarily change `platformio.ini`:

```ini
; Comment out OTA for first flash:
; upload_protocol = espota
; upload_port = 192.168.8.219
```

Click **Upload** (→). After that, all subsequent updates can be done wirelessly via OTA.

---

## Configuration

Edit `src/main.cpp` before flashing:

```cpp
// MQTT broker IP
IPAddress server(xxx, xxx, xxx, xxx); // change to your broker's IP

// MQTT topics (in reconnect())
client.subscribe("devlol/IoTlights/color"); // NeoPixel color control (hex string e.g. "#FF0030")
client.subscribe("devlol/IC-Ticker");       // ticker message

// Display orientation (0 = right-to-left scroll, 1 = left-to-right)
#define LEFTTORIGHT 0

// Number of MAX7219 modules
#define MAX_DEVICES 12

// Sleep schedule: device sleeps 23:00–06:00 automatically
```

### WiFi Setup (WiFiManager)

The device uses **WiFiManager** — no hardcoded WiFi credentials are needed.

- On first boot (or when no saved network is found), the ESP32 opens a captive portal AP:
  - **SSID:** `IC-Ticker`
  - **Password:** `interface`
- Connect to that AP and navigate to `192.168.4.1` to enter your WiFi credentials.
- Credentials are saved to flash and reused on every subsequent boot.
- While the portal is active, the no-WiFi message scrolls on the display.

> **eduroam / WPA2 Enterprise:** The `platformio.ini` pins a specific commit of WiFiManager that supports WPA2 Enterprise (e.g. eduroam at the Kunstuni). Don't update that library without testing first.

---

## OTA Updates (Over-The-Air)

Once the device is running and connected to WiFi, firmware can be updated wirelessly — no USB cable required.

OTA is already configured in `platformio.ini`:

```ini
upload_protocol = espota
upload_port = 192.168.8.219  ; Replace with your device's current IP
```

To upload over OTA, simply click **Upload** (→) in VS Code as usual — PlatformIO pushes the firmware over WiFi.

> **Find the device IP:** Check your router's DHCP table, or read it from the Serial Monitor on boot — the device prints its IP at startup.  
> OTA runs in a dedicated FreeRTOS task (`OTA_HANDLE`) so it doesn't block the display loop.

---

## MQTT Usage

### Send a ticker message

Publish any UTF-8 string (max ~95 chars) to `devlol/IC-Ticker`:

```bash
mosquitto_pub -h xxx.xxx.xxx.xxx -t "devlol/IC-Ticker" -m "Hello Interface Cultures!"
```

The message scrolls across the display 5 times, then the ticker returns to its default rotation.

### Control NeoPixel color

Publish a hex color string to `devlol/IoTlights/color`:

```bash
mosquitto_pub -h xxx.xxx.xxx.xxx -t "devlol/IoTlights/color" -m "#FF0030"
```

---

## Display Behaviour

The ticker cycles through content in this priority order:

1. **New MQTT message** — scrolls 5× then clears
2. **Default rotation** — alternates between `"IC Ticker"` and `"InterfaceCultures"`
3. **Every 60 seconds** — briefly shows the current **time**, then **date** (via NTP)

**Sleep:** The device automatically enters deep sleep at **23:00** and wakes at **06:00** (CET/CEST).  
**NTP server:** `europe.pool.ntp.org` — timezone string: `CET-1CEST,M3.5.0/02,M10.5.0/03`.

---

## Dependencies

Managed automatically by PlatformIO via `platformio.ini`:

| Library | Version | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `majicdesigns/MD_MAX72XX` | `^3.3.0` | Low-level MAX7219 driver |
| `majicdesigns/MD_Parola` | `^3.5.6` | Scrolling text effects |
| `knolleary/PubSubClient` | `^2.8` | MQTT client |
| `adafruit/Adafruit NeoPixel` | `^1.10.4` | Status LED ring |
| `tzapu/WiFiManager` | pinned commit `e1f59eb` | WiFi config portal + WPA2 Enterprise (eduroam) |

> ⚠️ **Do not update WiFiManager** without verifying eduroam / WPA2 Enterprise still works. The specific commit is pinned in `platformio.ini` intentionally.

